    "category": "Linux & Git",
    "question": "Share 10 Linux commands",
    "answer": "<div class=\"answer-rich\">\n  <h3>💻 <strong>Share 10 Linux commands</strong></h3>\n  <p>“Here are 10 essential Linux commands that I use daily for system administration, directory navigation, and troubleshooting:</p>\n  <ul style=\"margin-left:1.2rem;\">\n    <li><code>pwd</code> (Print Working Directory): Displays the absolute path of the directory you are currently in.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>pwd</code></li>\n    <li><code>ls</code> (List): Lists the files and directories in the current folder.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>ls -lah</code> (lists all files, including hidden ones, in long format with human-readable file sizes).</li>\n    <li><code>cd</code> (Change Directory): Navigates between directories in the filesystem.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>cd /var/log</code></li>\n    <li><code>mkdir</code> (Make Directory): Creates a new folder.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>mkdir -p /app/config</code> (the <code>-p</code> flag creates parent directories if they don't exist).</li>\n    <li><code>rm</code> (Remove): Deletes files or directories.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>rm -rf /tmp/cache</code> (recursively and forcefully deletes the directory).</li>\n    <li><code>cp</code> (Copy): Copies files or directories from one location to another.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>cp -r /src /dest</code></li>\n    <li><code>mv</code> (Move / Rename): Moves files or renames them.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>mv oldname.txt newname.txt</code></li>\n    <li><code>cat</code> (Concatenate): Outputs the contents of a file to the terminal.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>cat /etc/resolv.conf</code></li>\n    <li><code>chmod</code> (Change Mode): Modifies file and directory access permissions.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>chmod 755 script.sh</code></li>\n    <li><code>chown</code> (Change Owner): Modifies the owner and group of a file or directory.</li>\n    <li>Example*: <code>chown -R admin:webgroup /var/www</code>”</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>",
