    "answer": "<div class=\"answer-rich\">\n  <h3>🔀 <strong>What is the difference between Git and GitHub?</strong></h3>\n  <p>Comparing <strong>Erence  Git</strong> and <strong>Github</strong> in Git Version Control contexts:</p>\n  <h4>🔹 Core Architecture</h4>\n  <ul style=\"margin-left:1.2rem;\">\n    <li><strong>Erence  Git</strong>: Configures low-level direct bindings, local resource properties, or direct traffic paths.</li>\n    <li><strong>Github</strong>: Manages higher-level group abstractions, horizontal scaling, or distributed state boundaries.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <h4>🔹 Functional Differences & Control</h4>\n  <ul style=\"margin-left:1.2rem;\">\n    <li><strong>Routing & State</strong>: One operates statelessly at the node boundary, whereas the other preserves persistent identity state.</li>\n    <li><strong>Security Policies</strong>: One applies strict host access controls while the other handles routing, routing maps, or API authorization rules.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <h4>🔹 Interview Recommendation</h4>\n  <ul style=\"margin-left:1.2rem;\">\n    <li>Choose <strong>Erence  Git</strong> when targeting single-host boundaries, simple regional services, or stateless services.</li>\n    <li>Choose <strong>Github</strong> for automated orchestration, multi-zone recovery, and high availability systems.</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>",
